revision.text:
The '''Akiek''' are an ethnic and linguistic group in [[Tanzania]] and [[Kenya]], living in the [[Arusha Region]] in northern Tanzania and in southern Kenya, with an estimated population of 3,700 people.<ref name=lawrence>{{cite book |title=Tanzania And Its People |last=Lawrence |first=David |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2009 |publisher=CreateSpace |location= |isbn=1-4414-8692-5 |page=97 |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> The Akiek language is said to be a [[Endangered language|moribund language]]: only a few elderly speakers are left.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID%3D10510%26URL_DO%3DDO_TOPIC%26URL_SECTION%3D201.html |title=UNESCO |access-date=2018-10-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303192034/http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID%3D10510%26URL_DO%3DDO_TOPIC%26URL_SECTION%3D201.html |archive-date=2016-03-03 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> The Akiek in Tanzania now speak [[Maasai language|Maasai]], and those in Kenya speak [[Gikuyu language|Kikuyu]].<ref name=lawrence />

The Akiek are a subgroup of the Ogiek or [[Okiek people|Okiek]], who intermarried and lost contact with the core of the Ogiek. The terms Akiek and Okiek are sometimes used interchangeably and confusingly. The correct name of the original people is Ogiek.

