'''ChangeLab''' is a grassroots [[think tank]] located in downtown [[Oakland]], [[California]] with a satellite location in [[Seattle, Washington]].<ref name="dem">{{cite web|title=Debate: Does Marriage Equality Reinforce a Conservative Institution or Support Social Change?|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2013/3/28/debate_does_marriage_equality_reinforce_a|website=www.democracynow.org/|publisher=Democracy Now|accessdate=22 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="nation">{{cite web|last1=Schlanger|first1=Zoë|title=Scot Nakagawa: Dismantling the Fulcrum of White Supremacy|url=http://www.thenation.com/video/169560/scot-nakagawa-dismantling-fulcrum-white-supremacy|website=www.thenation.com|publisher=The Nation|accessdate=22 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="radio">{{cite web|title=soundcloud.com/sojournertruthradio/sojournertruthradio-4-25-13-2|url=https://soundcloud.com/sojournertruthradio/sojournertruthradio-4-25-13-2|website=soundcloud.com/|publisher=KPFK|accessdate=22 June 2014}}</ref>

==History==

ChangeLab started in Brooklyn and moved to Oakland in summer 2014. Soya Jung and Scot Nakagawa are senior partners.<ref name="radio"/> Yong Chan Miller is the research director.

==Media==
ChangeLab has published research papers, including the November 2012 "Left or Right of the Color Line: Asian Americans and the Racial Justice Movement" and the April 2013 "The Importance of Asian Americans? It's Not What You Think".

ChangeLab's blog is called Race Files. Bloggers include Scot Nakagawa, Soya Jung, and Alison Roh Park. Guest bloggers include Deepa Iyer, [[Prerna Lal]], Esther Wang, Naomi Ishisaka, [[Simon Tam (musician)|Simon Tam]], PaKou Her, Helena Wong, Daniel Hosang, and Yong Chan Miller. Topics on the blog include [[affirmative action]], [[racism]] (particularly anti-Asian racism), [[Asian Americans]], [[civil rights]], and [[white supremacy]].

