'''Laiuse Romani''' was a [[Romani language|Romani]] variety spoken in [[Estonia]]. It was a [[mixed language]] based on Romani and [[Estonian language|Estonian]].<ref name="smith">Smith, p. 365.</ref>

The [[Romani people]] first appeared to Estonia in the 17th century. According to rumors, they were first part of Swedish King [[Charles XII of Sweden|Charles XII]]'s Romani orchestra which he, after spending a winter in [[Laiuse Castle|Laiuse]], left behind. In 1841 all of the 44 Estonian Romani were collected and settled around [[Laiuse]] Parish. Their main stop was [[Raaduvere]] village, but they also lived in [[Tähkvere]], [[Jõgeva]] and its precincts. Before the [[Second World War]] there was 60 Romani in Laiuse.<ref name=eestigiid>{{cite web|title=Laiuse mustlased|url=http://www.eestigiid.ee/?SCat=7&CatID=4&ItemID=1560|publisher=eestigiid.ee|accessdate=23 September 2011|language=Estonian}}</ref> Laiuse Romani became [[language death|extinct]] in the [[German occupation of Estonia during World War II|German occupation]], when all its speakers were killed by the Nazis during the [[Porajmos]].<ref name="smith"/><ref name="m10"/>

==Linguistic features==
Laiuse Romani shares a number of linguistic features with [[Kalo Finnish Romani language|Finnish Kalo]],<ref name="m10">Matras, p. 10.</ref> such as [[Palatalization (phonetics)|palatalization]] of [[velar consonant]]s before [[front vowel]]s<ref>Matras, p. 49.</ref> and initial [[devoicing]].<ref>Matras, p. 54.</ref>

