The practice of [[Skin whitening|skin lightening]] and bleaching is a lucrative industry in Ghana, where higher value is placed upon being light skinned.<ref name=":2">{{cite journal|date=2008|title=I Like Your Colour – Skin Bleaching and Geographies of Ghana|journal=Feminist Review|issue=90|page=9|jstor=40663936|last1=Pierre|first1=Jemima|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=":53">{{Cite journal|last=Maswana|first=Jean – Claude|year=2009|title=Perspective on Africa-China's Emerging Economic Links|url=|journal=A Center-Periphery Perspective on Africa-China's Emerging Economic Links. African & Asian Studies|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> This practice has been present since the  sixteenth century and was influenced by contemporary practices, and it is a very longstanding and controversial topic. Skin bleaching is a practice where women and men use various chemical and cosmetics products to attempt to lighten or whiten the color of the skin. These products often contain one or both of two chemicals: hydroquinone and mercury and can sometimes lead to negative physical effects, such as cancer and can cause rash and flaky skin, as well as uneven light and dark patches on the skin. Because of the health risks involved with skin lightening, Ghana has implemented legislation against the use of skin lightening products. Though the products have recently been banned, Ghanaian women can still acquire them through illegal means or use homemade skin lightening chemicals.<ref name="Foluo">{{cite journal|date=2008|title=The Lighter Side of Marriage|journal=African and Asian Studies|volume=8|issue=1/2|page=125|doi=10.1163/156921009X413180|ref=Foluo|last1=Foluo|first1=J.Konadu|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name="Pierre">{{cite book|title=The predicament of blackness postcolonial Ghana and the politics of race|date=2013|publisher=The University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-92304-8|location=Chicago|page=101|ref=Pierre|last1=Pierre|first1=Jemima|accessdate=}}</ref> 

Light skinned is frequently marketed via billboards and posters that feature light skinned models, playing on the public perception that looking [[multiracial]] or having lighter skin makes one more attractive.<ref name=":2" /> Some Ghanians also believe that if a lighter-skinned person is  in a position of power, that they bleached to get into that position and is bleaching to maintain it.<ref name="Pierre" /> Historians such as Jemima Pierre theorize that the desire for lighter colored skin stem from [[apartheid]] and the British colonization of West Africa.<ref name=":2" /> White skin asserted class privilege and distinct racial privilege, prompting many Ghanians to bleach their skin to achieve a similar color.<ref name="Pierre" /><ref name=":2" /> Over time this also became a major determinant of beauty, especially among Ghanian women, and by the 1980s skin bleaching had spread throughout all socioeconomic classes of women.<ref name="Foluo" /><ref name=":4">{{Cite journal|last=Lartey|first=Margaret|last2=Krampa|first2=Francis D.|last3=Abdul-Rahman|first3=Mubarak|last4=Quarcoo|first4=Naa L.|last5=Yamson|first5=Phaedra|last6=Hagan|first6=Paa G.|last7=Tettey|first7=Yao|last8=Gyasi|first8=Richard|last9=Adjei|first9=Andrew A.|date=2017-01-01|title=Use of skin-lightening products among selected urban communities in Accra, Ghana|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/ijd.13449/abstract|journal=International Journal of Dermatology|language=en|volume=56|issue=1|pages=32–39|doi=10.1111/ijd.13449|issn=1365-4632}}</ref> Despite being a common practice among Ghanians, lower class people are often openly ridiculed for skin bleaching. Blacks who bleach their skin (regardless of socioeconomic status) are often ridiculed for aspiring and ultimately failing to become white.<ref name="Pierre" />

