The '''Wala''' or '''Waala''' live in [[Upper West Region]] of [[Ghana]]. They are a predominantly [[Muslim]] people who are the founders of the city of [[Wa, Ghana|Wa]] and the [[Kingdom of Wala]]. They speak the [[Wali language (Ghana)|Wali language]], which belongs to the [[Gur languages|Gur]] group. There are 84,800 speakers of the language as of 2013.<ref>[https://www.ethnologue.com/language/wlx Wali] Ethnologue, retrieved 25 October 2016</ref> Their neighbors are the [[Birifor people|Birifor]], [[Dagaaba people|Dagaaba]], and [[Vagla people]]s.<ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_map.asp?name=GH&seq=10 Language Map of Ghana]</ref>

Their culture is similar to other [[Gur languages|Gur]]-speaking, [[Senoufo]] and [[Mandé peoples|Mande]] groups in northern [[Cote d'Ivoire]], [[Burkina Faso]] and [[Mali]]. They are known for their impressive [[Sudano-Sahelian]] style [[mosque]]s and palaces. They are ruled by their traditional ruler, the [[Wa-Na]] whose traditional residence is a mud-brick built palace in [[Wa, Ghana|Wa]].

According to the 1921 census of Ghana the Wala numbered 16,905, although it is thought that that census missed some of the small villages in the [[Wa District]]. This meant that at the time they were outnumbered in Wa District by the Dagarti. In many ways the difference between Dagarti and Wa is which side of the rebellion they were on in 1894, those who sided with the Wa-Na coming to be the Wala, and those who rebelled being considered part of the Dagarti people. The number of Dagarti was so high because the British had imposed the pre-1894 boundaries of the [[Kingdom of Wala]] as the boundaries of the District of Wa.<ref>Ivor Wilks, ''Wa and the Wala: Islam and polity in northwestern Ghana'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1988), p. 13</ref>
